<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,1494,1631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Though Hardwicke did not acknowledge him, it was Roxburgh (in litt.) who suggested ‘rotundifolia’ as the specific epithet for this species. There is a specimen in BM that has the same number as the drawing referred to by 
<bibRefCitation author="Britten J." box="[361,534,1568,1595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="235 - 241" refId="ref8948" refString="Britten J. 1906. Hardwicke's botanical drawings. Journal of Botany, British and foreign 44: 235 - 241." type="journal article" year="1906">Britten (1906)</bibRefCitation>
. There is also a drawing in the British Library set (Vol. IV no. 5) which is presumably the one that Smith had copied for the plate in 
<emphasis box="[896,1061,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Exotic Botany</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Smith J. E." box="[1077,1217,1604,1631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref10343" refString="Smith J. E. 1804 - 1805. Exotic Botany. Two volumes. R. Taylor &amp; Co., London." type="book" year="1804">
Smith 
<date box="[1156,1217,1604,1631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1804" valueMax="1805">1804</date>
</bibRefCitation>
–1805: t. 113).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
